      <section id="sect-00009">
      <title>Correlation Does Not Imply Causation</title>
      <para id="para-00085">One of the most common fallacies about statistics has to do with the relationship between two data sets. In the data set “Public” (data from data.ed.gov), we find that the correlation coefficient between the 75<sup>th</sup> percentile math SAT score and the 75<sup>th</sup> percentile verbal SAT score is 0.92, which is really strong. The slope of the regression line that predicts the verbal score from the math score is 0.729, which we might interpret as follows: “If the 75<sup>th</sup> percentile math SAT score goes up by 10 points, we’d expect the corresponding verbal SAT score to go up by just over 7 points.” Does the increasing math score <emphasis effect="italics">cause</emphasis> the increase in the verbal score? Probably not… What’s really going on is that there’s a third variable that’s affecting them both: to raise the SAT math score by 10 points, a school will recruit students who do better on the SAT in general; these students will also naturally have higher SAT verbal scores. This third variable is sometimes called a <emphasis effect="italics">lurking variable</emphasis> or a <emphasis effect="italics">confounding variable</emphasis>. Unless all possible lurking variables are ruled out, we cannot conclude that one thing causes another.</para>
      <note class="people-mathematics" id="note-00023">
      <title>Francis Galton, Karl Pearson, and Ronald Fisher</title>
      
      <para id="para-00087">Francis Galton, Karl Pearson, and Ronald Fisher are among the founding fathers of the field of statistics. Galton (1822 – 1911) came up with the formula for the standard deviation, and he devised a machine (called the <emphasis effect="italics">quincunx</emphasis> or <emphasis effect="italics">bean machine</emphasis>) that verified the connection we noted earlier between the coin flipping experiment and the normal distribution. He also was a pioneer in linear regression.</para>
      <para id="para-00088">Pearson (1857 – 1936) expanded on Galton’s work with regression, deriving the formula for the correlation coefficient that is used today. (In fact, it’s often called the Pearson correlation.) He popularized (and, according to some sources, invented) the histogram as a visualization tool. He is also remembered for his development of the theory of hypothesis testing, one of the most important tools in scientific data analysis.</para>
      <para id="para-00089">Fisher (1890 – 1962) is possibly the most important figure in 20<sup>th</sup> century statistics. His theoretical work spawned numerous new analysis techniques; among the most common is Analysis of Variance (which uses the <emphasis effect="italics">F</emphasis>-distribution instead of the normal distribution; the “<emphasis effect="italics">F</emphasis>” stands for “Fisher”). He also popularized the use of the 68-95-99.7 Rule.</para>
      <para id="para-00090">Each of these men, based on his contribution to the field, is deserving of his own profile. So, why are we lumping them together? What do they all have in common? It all goes back to Galton, who was fascinated by the work published by his cousin, Charles Darwin. Galton was particularly fascinated with the concept of taking Darwin’s natural selection and applying it to the human race. In one work he published, Galton claimed that, thanks to superior genetics achieved through proper breeding, the British upper classes possessed enhanced intelligence. He called it <emphasis effect="italics">Hereditary Genius</emphasis>; his book with that title was published in 1870. It was his obsession with this idea, that mankind could be improved by leveraging genetics and the processes of evolution, that led him to his discoveries in statistics.</para>
      <para id="para-00091">Pearson took these ideas and translated them into a much bigger scale. In his “National Life from the Standpoint of Science,” Pearson declared that, rather than provide social welfare to improve the fortunes of the poor, nations would be better off waging “war with inferior races.” In 1925, he coauthored a paper titled “The Problem of Alien Immigration into Great Britain,” in which he argued against allowing Jewish immigration into the country, saying that they were “inferior physically and mentally to the native population.”</para>
      <para id="para-00092">Fisher also worked in genetics; his paper “On the correlation between relatives on the supposition of Mendelian inheritance” bridged the gap between the classical genetics of Mendel and the statistical theories that he and Pearson, among others, had devised. Fisher’s interest in genetics took root early on; as an undergraduate at Cambridge University, he founded a club whose members, in his words, would be “agents of a new phase of evolution” whose goal was to evangelize “not by precept only, but by example, the doctrine of a new natural ability of worth and blood.”</para>
      <para id="para-00093">If all of this is setting off Nazi alarm bells in the back of your mind, there’s a good reason for it. Galton invented the term for these ideas that he, Pearson, and Fisher championed: <emphasis effect="italics">eugenics</emphasis>. When Pearson died, he left a portion of his estate to fund an academic position at the University of London: the Galton Chair of Eugenics. Pearson was the first person to be named to that position. The club that Fisher founded was called the Cambridge University Undergraduates Eugenics Society; the quotation above comes from the club’s minutes.</para>
      <para id="para-00094">Eugenics really found a home when its ideas were espoused abroad; laws were passed that allowed for the forced sterilization of people with mental illnesses, physical impairments like blindness, people suffering from epilepsy, and a host of other maladies. In some areas, a Board of Eugenics was established to decide which citizens would be forcibly sterilized. It may surprise you to learn that all of this happened in the United States, where over 60,000 people were subjected to sterilization against their will.</para>
      <para id="para-00095">It was the American system that influenced the Nazi regime, who took eugenics to an unimaginably horrible level. Though they, too, started with sterilization programs, eventually they began simply killing those who had mental or physical disabilities. Eventually, anything that the regime believed was a genetic deficiency would qualify a person for this euthanasia program, including race. An estimated six million Jews were killed as a result of this program, now commonly called the Holocaust.</para>
      <para id="para-00096">Though it wouldn’t be fair to say that the development of statistics led to the Holocaust, we can’t deny that many statistical techniques were developed in the service of eugenics, which eventually inspired the Holocaust. Galton, Pearson, and Fisher all used statistics to try to validate and popularize eugenics, and if we measure by their impact on the world at large, they were successful. While we remember them for their positive contributions to scientific practice, we must never forget the consequences of their works.</para>
      </note>
      <note class="who-knew" id="note-00024">
      <title>Using Data For Good</title>
      <para id="para-00097">Statistics can also be used for good. Dr. Talithia Williams talks about using data and statistics to make informed health decisions in her TED talk, found here:</para>
      <para id="para-00098">VIDEO: <link url="https://openstax.org/r/TED-Talk_talithia_williams">Dr. Talithia Williams’ TED Talk</link></para>
      <para id="para-00099">She also talks about how she uses her statistical skills for the greater good of mankind in her interview with thisisstatistics.org, found here: <link url="https://openstax.org/r/collecting-data-affect-change-interview-statisticiantalithia-williams">https://openstax.org/r/collecting-data-affect-change-interview-statisticiantalithia-williams</link></para>
      </note>
